  {
    "id": "vowel-harmony",
    "title": "Vowel Harmony",
    "description": "Understand the fundamental rule that governs Turkish suffixes",
    "difficulty": "beginner",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "Vowel harmony is the most important rule in Turkish grammar. Suffixes change their vowels to match the last vowel of the root word."
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": "Turkish Vowel Groups",
        "table": {
          "headers": ["Type", "Back Vowels", "Front Vowels"],
          "rows": [
            ["Unrounded", "a, ı", "e, i"],
            ["Rounded", "o, u", "ö, ü"]
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "Two-way harmony (e/a): After back vowels (a, ı, o, u) use 'a'. After front vowels (e, i, ö, ü) use 'e'. Example: evler (houses) vs odalar (rooms)."
      },
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "Four-way harmony (i/ı/u/ü): The suffix vowel matches both frontness and roundedness. After a→ı, after e→i, after o→u, after ö→ü."
      }
    ],
    "exercises": [
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "ev + ler/lar → ev___",
        "answer": "ler",
        "hint": "'e' is a front vowel, so use 'ler'"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "oda + ler/lar → oda___",
        "answer": "lar",
        "hint": "'a' is a back vowel, so use 'lar'"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "göz + ler/lar → göz___",
        "answer": "ler",
        "hint": "'ö' is a front vowel, so use 'ler'"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "kuş + ler/lar → kuş___",
        "answer": "lar",
        "hint": "'u' is a back vowel, so use 'lar'"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "plurals",
    "title": "Plural Suffix -ler / -lar",
    "description": "Learn how to make Turkish nouns plural",
    "difficulty": "beginner",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "Turkish plurals are simple: add -ler after front vowels (e, i, ö, ü) and -lar after back vowels (a, ı, o, u)."
      },
      {
        "type": "example",
        "content": "Examples of plural formation",
        "examples": [
          { "tr": "ev → evler", "en": "house → houses" },
          { "tr": "araba → arabalar", "en": "car → cars" },
          { "tr": "göz → gözler", "en": "eye → eyes" },
          { "tr": "kuş → kuşlar", "en": "bird → birds" }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "exercises": [
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "kitap → kitap___",
        "answer": "lar",
        "hint": "Last vowel 'a' is a back vowel"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "kedi → kedi___",
        "answer": "ler",
        "hint": "Last vowel 'i' is a front vowel"
      },
      {
        "type": "sentence_build",
        "english": "The cats are small",
        "words": ["küçük", "kediler"],
        "correctOrder": ["kediler", "küçük"]
      },
      {
        "type": "sentence_build",
        "english": "The houses are big",
        "words": ["büyük", "evler"],
        "correctOrder": ["evler", "büyük"]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "present-continuous",
    "title": "Present Continuous Tense (-yor)",
    "description": "Learn to express actions happening right now",
    "difficulty": "beginner",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "The present continuous tense is formed by adding -yor to the verb stem, followed by personal suffixes. The vowel before -yor follows 4-way harmony (ı/i/u/ü)."
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": "Conjugation of 'gelmek' (to come)",
        "table": {
          "headers": ["Pronoun", "Turkish", "English"],
          "rows": [
            ["Ben", "geliyorum", "I am coming"],
            ["Sen", "geliyorsun", "You are coming"],
            ["O", "geliyor", "He/she is coming"],
            ["Biz", "geliyoruz", "We are coming"],
            ["Siz", "geliyorsunuz", "You (pl) are coming"],
            ["Onlar", "geliyorlar", "They are coming"]
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "If the verb stem ends in a vowel, drop it before adding -yor. Example: bekle-mek → bekl-iyor (is waiting)."
      }
    ],
    "exercises": [
      {
        "type": "conjugation",
        "verb": "gitmek (to go)",
        "tense": "Present Continuous",
        "pronouns": ["Ben", "Sen", "O", "Biz", "Siz", "Onlar"],
        "answers": {
          "Ben": "gidiyorum",
          "Sen": "gidiyorsun",
          "O": "gidiyor",
          "Biz": "gidiyoruz",
          "Siz": "gidiyorsunuz",
          "Onlar": "gidiyorlar"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "Ben okula ___",
        "answer": "gidiyorum",
        "hint": "I am going to school"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "O kitap ___",
        "answer": "okuyor",
        "hint": "He/she is reading a book"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "questions",
    "title": "Question Formation (mı/mi/mu/mü)",
    "description": "Learn to ask yes/no questions in Turkish",
    "difficulty": "beginner",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "Yes/no questions are formed by adding the question particle mı/mi/mu/mü after the word being questioned. It follows 4-way vowel harmony."
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": "Question particle selection",
        "table": {
          "headers": ["Last Vowel", "Particle", "Example"],
          "rows": [
            ["a, ı", "mı", "güzel mi? → Is it beautiful?"],
            ["e, i", "mi", "iyi mi? → Is it good?"],
            ["o, u", "mu", "bu mu? → Is this?"],
            ["ö, ü", "mü", "gül mü? → Is it a rose?"]
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "example",
        "content": "Question examples",
        "examples": [
          { "tr": "Sen Türk müsün?", "en": "Are you Turkish?" },
          { "tr": "Bu kitap mı?", "en": "Is this a book?" },
          { "tr": "Geliyor musun?", "en": "Are you coming?" }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "exercises": [
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "Bu güzel ___?",
        "answer": "mi",
        "hint": "Last vowel of 'güzel' is 'e' → mi"
      },
      {
        "type": "fill_blank",
        "sentence": "O bir doktor ___?",
        "answer": "mu",
        "hint": "Last vowel of 'doktor' is 'o' → mu"
      },
      {
        "type": "sentence_build",
        "english": "Is this a cat?",
        "words": ["mi", "bir", "bu", "kedi"],
        "correctOrder": ["bu", "bir", "kedi", "mi"]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "past-tense",
    "title": "Past Tense (-di / -dı)",
    "description": "Express completed actions in the past",
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "explanation",
        "content": "The definite past tense (witnessed past) uses -di/-dı/-du/-dü suffixes. After voiceless consonants (ç, f, h, k, p, s, ş, t), use -ti/-tı/-tu/-tü instead."
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": "Conjugation of 'gelmek' (to come) - Past Tense",
        "table": {
          "headers": ["Pronoun", "Turkish", "English"],
          "rows": [
            ["Ben", "geldim", "I came"],
            ["Sen", "geldin", "You came"],
            ["O", "geldi", "He/she came"],
            ["Biz", "geldik", "We came"],
            ["Siz", "geldiniz", "You (pl) came"],
            ["Onlar", "geldiler", "They came"]
          ]
        }
      }
    ],
    "exercises": [
      {
